<li>Differential effects of invasion by and phagocytosis of Salmonella typhimurium on apoptosis in human macrophages : potential role of Rho -- GTPases and Akt Maria Forsberg , * Robert Blomgran , * Maria Lerm , * Eva Särndahl , † Said M. Sebti , ‡ Andrew Hamilton , § Olle Stendahl , * and Limin Zheng * ,1 Divisions of * Medical Microbiology , IMK , and † Cell Biology , IBK , Linköping University , Sweden ; ‡ Drug Program , H. Lee Mofﬁtt Cancer Center & Research Institute , Department of Oncology , University of Sou Tampa ; and § Department of Chemistry , Yale University , New Haven , Connecticut Discovery th Florida , Abstract : In addition to direct activation of caspase-1 and induction of apoptosis by SipB , invasive Salmonella stimulates multiple signaling pathways that are key regulators of host cell survival .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12960245" target="_blank">12960245</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activation of these pathways is independent of SPI-1 and not tied to activation of Rho GTPases and actin rearrangements ( described above ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cooperative activation of PI3K by Ras and Rho family small GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29276700" target="_blank">29276700</a>]<br></li>
<li>Importantly , extended activation of Rho GTPases by SopE can be sensed by host cells by NOD1 , resulting in NF - B activation and proinﬂammatory signaling ( 17 ) ; antagonism of SopE by SptP therefore represents an important mechanism to prevent the activation of host immune defenses .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27920299" target="_blank">27920299</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , Clostridium difﬁcile toxins and Escherichia coli cytotoxic necrotizing factor 1 enhance permeability by regulating the activity of Rho GTPases and disrupting actin microﬁlaments ( 13 , 26 , 27 ) , and enteropathogenic E. coli induces tight junction dysfunction via phosphorylation of myosin light chains ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12540569" target="_blank">12540569</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , through a carefully orchestrated `` yin and yang , '' Salmonella reversibly activates Rho family GTPases to induce its own uptake and the production of proinflammatory cytokines .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Friebel , A. , Ilchmann , H. , Aepfelbacher , M. , Ehrbar , K. , Machleidt , W. , and Hardt , W.D. ( 2001 ) SopE and SopE2 from Salmonella typhimurium activate different sets of Rho GTPases of the host cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15469433" target="_blank">15469433</a>]<br></li>
<li>T H E J O U R N A L O F C E L L B I O L O G JCB : ARTICLE Differential activation and function of Rho GTPases during Salmonella -- host cell interactions Jayesh C. Patel and Jorge E. Galán Section of Microbial Pathogenesis , Yale University School of Medicine , Boyer Center for Molecular Medicine , New Haven , CT 06536 S almonella enterica , the cause of food poisoning and typhoid fever , has evolved sophisticated mechanisms to modulate Rho family guanosine triphosphatases ( GTPases ) to mediate speciﬁc cellular responses such as actin remodeling , macropinocytosis , and nuclear responses .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , Wnt signaling has additional effects that could contribute to cancer formation , including the activation of genes involved in glutamine metabolism like glutamine synthetase14 and the control of cytoskeleton organization , cell-to-cell adhesion , cell polarity , and cell motility .15 These latter effects can also involve Rho GTPase signaling .16,17 ily of small GTPases controlling cell polarity , motility , differentiation , apoptosis , and proliferation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18242605" target="_blank">18242605</a>]<br></li>
<li>This leads to the activation of host Rho GTPases resulting in global actin cytoskeletal rearrangements , membrane ruffling and bacterial uptake by macropinocytosis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25308535" target="_blank">25308535</a>]<br></li>
<li>Salmonella-Induced Inflammatory Responses in Intestinal Epithelial Cells As described above , the activation of Rho GTPases leads to cytoskeletal rearrangements associated with membrane ruffling and internalization of Salmonella .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>SifA is a structural homologue of another bacterial effector that acts as a GTP-exchange factor for Rho family GTPases and can bind GDP-RhoA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20739463" target="_blank">20739463</a>]<br></li>
<li>The most well-known substrates for GGTase-I include Rho -- GTPases , such as Rac , Rho , and Cdc42 [ 28 , 46 , 47 ] , which are essential for Salmonella-induced cytoskeletal and nuclear responses [ 26 , 41 , 48 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12960245" target="_blank">12960245</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE was characterized as a GEF for Rho GTPases by its ability to stimulate in vitro nucleotide exchange on Cdc42 , Rac1 , and RhoA , and is required for entry .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11256999" target="_blank">11256999</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE activates caspase-1 and elicits IL-1 and IL-18 production by enterocytes The S. Typhimurium effector-protein SopE is a guanine nucleotide exchange factor ( GEF ) that activates Rho GTPases such as Rac1 and CDC42 [ 56 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21726991" target="_blank">21726991</a>]<br></li>
<li>After trans-location , together with effectors SopE and SopE2 , SopB interferes with cellular functions by activating the host Rho GTPase Cdc42 [ 31 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24075929" target="_blank">24075929</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the active state , Rho GTPases interact with effector-proteins , such as kinases , lipases , and oxidases to alter their activity ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22362774" target="_blank">22362774</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar to the T3SS1 effectors , Rck activates the Rho GTPases Rac1 and Cdc42 to promote Salmonella uptake ( 22 -- 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24126528" target="_blank">24126528</a>]<br></li>
<li>Proteins injected into the host cell by Salmonella activate the Rho GTPases , Rac1 and Cdc42 , to induce actin polym-erization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17693642" target="_blank">17693642</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17693642" target="_blank">17693642</a>]<br></li>
<li>IQGAP1 is a large scaffolding protein that binds actin and several small G proteins , including those in the Rho GTPase family , such as Cdc42 and Rac1 , but does not bind RhoA itself [ 34,43,44 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19956712" target="_blank">19956712</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , we observed that the S. enterica serovar Typhimurium SPI-1 secreted effector-protein SopE participates in both apical and basolateral bacterial internalization ; SopE and the closely related SopE2 activate Rho GTPases directly by promoting GTP binding ( 14 , 19 , 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>We next focused on the SPI-1-en-coded effector-proteins SopB , SopE , and SopE2 that speciﬁcally activate Rho family GTPases , and SipA that directly interacts with actin ( McGhie et al. , 2001 ) , using mutant bacterial strains lacking expression of these proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23159054" target="_blank">23159054</a>]<br></li>
<li>Collectively , these results show that in vivo , the Salmo-nella effector-proteins SopE , SopE2 , and SopB differentially activate Rho family GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>SPI1 effectors , such as SopE , SopE2 , and SopB , activate the Rho GTPases Rac-1 and Cdc42 , which leads to actin cytoskeletal reorganization and eventually bacterial internalization ( 2 , 15 , 28 , 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12819095" target="_blank">12819095</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE or SopE2 activate the Rho GTPases Rac-1 and Cdc42 or only Cdc42 , respectively , leading to actin assembly , membrane ruffling and bacterial internalization [ 22 -- 24 , 54 , 56 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29522566" target="_blank">29522566</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SPI-1 effectors SopE , SopE2 , and SopB in a pathogen , as well as the Rho GTPases Cdc42 , Rac1 , and RhoG in a host , are required for orchestrated and efﬁcient invasion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20028809" target="_blank">20028809</a>]<br></li>
<li>More specifically , effectors SopE and SopE2 are guanine nucleotide exchange factors ( GEF ) for the Rho family GTPases Rac1 and Cdc42 , which cause actin polymerization and membrane ruffling ( Rac1 ) , as well as nuclear responses and cytokine production ( Cdc42 ) [ 8,9 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18541478" target="_blank">18541478</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE and SopE2 are guanine nucleotide exchange factors that activate the Rho GTPases Cdc42 and Rac1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17189373" target="_blank">17189373</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE , SopE2 and SopB target the RhoGTPase switch and promote activation of the Rho family members Cdc42 and Rac , leading to actin remodeling .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16182381" target="_blank">16182381</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE can efficiently and directly activate members of the Rho GTPase family of small G-proteins , including Rac-1 , Rac-2 , Cdc42 , RhoG , and , to a lesser extent , RhoA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11036630" target="_blank">11036630</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE , SopE2 , and SopB activate the Rho GTPases Rac-1 and Cdc42 , which induces cytoskeletal changes and membrane rufﬂing but also triggers several mitogen-acti-vated protein kinase pathways , resulting in the activation of NF - B ( 2 , 15 , 18 , 28 , 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12819095" target="_blank">12819095</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rho , Rac and Cdc42 GTPases regulate the assembly of multimolecular focal complexes associated with actin stress fibers , lamellipodia , and filopodia .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tapon , N. , and Hall , A. ( 1997 ) Rho , Rac and Cdc42 GTPases regulate the organization of the actin cytoskeleton .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18005098" target="_blank">18005098</a>]<br></li>
<li>SPI-1 effectors also activate the Rho fami ly GTPases Cdc42 and Rac-1 , and inhibition of Cdc42 and Rac-1 prenylation inhibits Salmonella-induced macrophage death ( Forsberg et al. 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15791954" target="_blank">15791954</a>]<br></li>
<li>Whereas the interaction between Salmonella effectors SopE and SptP and Rho GTPases Cdc42 and Rac1 have been structurally characterized ( 20 , 21 ) , there has been no structural information of the Salmonella effector SopB and its interaction with Cdc42 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22362774" target="_blank">22362774</a>]<br></li>
<li>Through its TTSS , Salmonella delivers SopE , SopE2 , and SopB , which differentially activate different Rho family GTPase members either directly ( SopE and SopE2 ) or indirectly via the stimulation of the endogenous exchange factor SGEF ( SopB ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cytoskeletal rearrangements are also accomplished indirectly through the overlapping functions of the effectors SopB ( also known as SigD ) , SopE , and SopE2 that activate Rho GTPases such as Cdc42 and Rac1 ( 10 , 11 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among these effectors , SopE , SopE2 , and SopB , on the pathogen side , as well as the Rho GTPases Cdc42 , Rac1 , and RhoG , on the host side , are required for a coordinated and efﬁcient invasion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23027532" target="_blank">23027532</a>]<br></li>
