<li>In one scenario , a toxin B-sensitive Rho family member that has no yet been examined is necessary for basolateral bacterial internalization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>As with other GTPases , Rho family members cycle between protein SopE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11256999" target="_blank">11256999</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cells were treated with genistein or DMSO control and then microinjected with purified GST ± SopE protein , which is an exchange factor for Rho family GTPases , along with FITC-labelled dextran to identify microinjected cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11736992" target="_blank">11736992</a>]<br></li>
<li>This clostridial toxin monoglucosylates Rho family members at a conserved threonine residue in the GTPase nucleotide binding pocket , rendering them inactive ( 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>A potential candidate is RhoG ( Vincent et al. , 1992 ) , a Rho family GTPase that has been previously shown to mediate dorsal ruffling and macropinocytosis in fibroblasts ( Ellerbroek et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among these is SopE , which has been shown to be a guanine nucleotide exchange factor for Rho family GTPases ( Hardt et al. , 1998 ; Rudolph et al. , 1999 ; Stender et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11437833" target="_blank">11437833</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hardt et al. reported that S. enterica serovar Typhimurium SopE has in vitro nucleotide exchange activity on four Rho family members : Rac1 , Cdc42 , RhoA , and RhoG ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although we have now examined the four Rho GTPases shown by Hardt et al. ( 19 ) to serve as substrates for SopE , over ﬁfteen Rho family members have been identiﬁed to date , some of which might be found to have essential roles in basolateral actin remodeling .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>This mechanism appears to be used by another RhoA eukaryotic effector , mDia1 , to distinguish RhoA from other members of the Rho family ( Rose et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25620407" target="_blank">25620407</a>]<br></li>
<li>During cell spreading , Rho family members function sequentially , with initial activation of Cdc42 , followed by Rac1 and RhoA ( Nobes and Hall , 1995 ; Ridley et al. , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11256999" target="_blank">11256999</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been shown to be activated by interaction with fatty acids , such as arachidonic acid , and several members of the Rho family of small GTPases , such as RhoA and Rac1 , and by cleavage of the amino-terminal regulatory domain by caspase-3 during apoptosis ( Mukai et al. , 1994 ; Amano et al. , 1996 ; Takahashi et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16611232" target="_blank">16611232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two of these bacterial effectors are SopE and SopE2 , which are highly related bacterial proteins with the capacity to catalyze nucleotide exchange on Rho family GTPase members ( Hardt et al. , 1998 ; Bakshi et al. , 2000 ; Stender et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro , SopE and SopE2 exhibit similar specificity , catalyzing exchange on several members of the Rho family of GTPases , including Rac1 and Cdc42 ( Hardt et al. , 1998 ; Stender et al. , 2000 ; Friebel et al. , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previous studies have defined the precise mechanisms by which two Salmonella-encoded exchange factors , SopE and its highly related paralogue SopE2 , catalyze the activation of Rho GTPase family members ( Hardt et al. , 1998 ; Friebel et al. , 2001 ; Buchwald et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>The related proteins ExoS and YopE have been shown recently to posses in vitro GAP activity toward a broader range of Rho family members than SptP ( Goehring et al. , 1999 ; Von Pawel-Rammingen et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11163217" target="_blank">11163217</a>]<br></li>
<li>This region makes extensive contacts to the GAP domain of SptP , and in so doing adopts a conformation very similar to that of Switch I in other GAP complexes with Rho family members ( Hirshberg et al. , 1997 ; Nassar et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11163217" target="_blank">11163217</a>]<br></li>
<li>YopE is known to stimulate GTP hydrolysis in vitro of several members of the Rho family of G-proteins , including Cdc42 ( Aili et al. , 2003 ; Von Pawel-Rammingen et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074912" target="_blank">17074912</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Rho family of proteins comprises small Ras-related GTP-binding proteins that cycle between active ( GTPbound ) and inactive ( GDP-bound ) states .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rho GDP dissociation inhibitor ( GDI ) is a general regulator of these Rho family members that forms a complex with their GDP-bound inactive form and inhibits their activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11036594" target="_blank">11036594</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Rckmediated signaling cascade requires the small Rho GTPase family members , Rac1 and Cdc42 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29276700" target="_blank">29276700</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the Rho GTPase family ( for example Cdc42 , Rac1 , and RhoA ) are low molecular weight proteins containing two flexible regulatory switch regions , termed switch I and II , that bind and hydrolyze GTP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22362774" target="_blank">22362774</a>]<br></li>
<li>It encodes two closely related type III effector proteins , SopE and SopE2 , which , following translocation , directly engage and activate two Rho family members , Cdc42 and Rac [ 11,12 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16182381" target="_blank">16182381</a>]<br></li>
<li>More specifically , effectors SopE and SopE2 are guanine nucleotide exchange factors ( GEF ) for the Rho family GTPases Rac1 and Cdc42 , which cause actin polymerization and membrane ruffling ( Rac1 ) , as well as nuclear responses and cytokine production ( Cdc42 ) [ 8,9 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18541478" target="_blank">18541478</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both SopE and SopE2 exhibit distinct speciﬁcities for Rho family members in vitro and in vivo ; SopE is capable of activating Cdc42 and Rac1 whereas SopE2 displays a preference for Cdc42 [ 10,14 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15694851" target="_blank">15694851</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our experiments suggested that SCV positioning might be regulated by members of the Rho GTPase family , acting via ROCK activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18411289" target="_blank">18411289</a>]<br></li>
<li>RhoA is a member of the Rho GTPase family that functions as major molecular switches that cycle between the GDP-bound inactive state and the GTP-bound active state .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22740689" target="_blank">22740689</a>]<br></li>
<li>SseJ is a RhoA-dependent GCAT Rho family GTPases act as binary molecular switches that cycle between the GDP bound ( inactive state ) and the GTP bound ( active state ) in response to a variety of stimuli ( Moon and Zheng , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25620407" target="_blank">25620407</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hoffman , G. R. , Nassar , N. , and Cerione , R. A. ( 2000 ) Structure of the Rho family GTP-binding protein Cdc42 in complex with multifunctional regulator GDI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22362774" target="_blank">22362774</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the contribution of the specific Rho family members to Salmonella -- host cell interactions has remained elusive .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>SigD has also been shown to activate a GTPase of the Rho family , the RhoG protein , in S. Typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>A downstream effect of these ( as yet unidentified ) Rho GTPases is recruitment of the Arp2/3 complex to membrane ruffles and its activation via Scar1 , a WASP family protein ( 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>In many circumstances , Arp2/3 complex-mediated actin remodeling occurs downstream of signaling by members of the Rho family of monomeric GTPases , particularly Rac1 and Cdc42 ( 34 , 37 , 44 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12704163" target="_blank">12704163</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , S. enterica modulates Rho family GTPases with bacterial proteins that precisely mimic the function of endogenous modulators of this family of small GTP-binding proteins ( Galán , 2001 ; Stebbins and Galán , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>GGTI-298 is known to inhibit different members of Rho family of the gamma subunit of trimeric G proteins ( 7 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12540569" target="_blank">12540569</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rho GTPases , polyphosphoinositides , and various adaptor proteins regulate the activity of WASP ( Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome protein ) family proteins , which in turn bind and stimulate the actin nucleation activity of the Arp2/3 complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of the different Rho family GTPases leads to speciﬁc cellular responses , such as actin remodeling , and the stimulation of nuclear responses , such as the production of IL-8 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the known upstream components , members of the Rho family of the small G proteins , such as Cdc42 , have been identified as important modulators of MAPK cascades in S. cerevisiae ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12016210" target="_blank">12016210</a>]<br></li>
<li>The best-known protein substrates for GGTase-I include the Rho family of small G-proteins ( Cdc42 , Rac , and Rho ) , which are , as mentioned above , key regulators of the structure of the actin cytoskeleton ( 15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12540569" target="_blank">12540569</a>]<br></li>
<li>The recruitment and activation of the small Rho GTPase family members impact the actin dynamics of the host cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29276700" target="_blank">29276700</a>]<br></li>
<li>Members of the Rho family of small GTPases are critical regulators of actin structure , and in nonpolarized cells , the GTPase Cdc42 has been shown to modulate Salmonella entry .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11256999" target="_blank">11256999</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ability of S. ﬂexneri to invade epithelial cells is also dependent on the activity of members of the GTPase family , including Rho , Rac and Cdc42 [ 96 , 97 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10961343" target="_blank">10961343</a>]<br></li>
<li>One key cellular target is the Rho family of small GTPases , which are central regulators of eukaryotic cytoskeletal dynamics [ 9 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16182381" target="_blank">16182381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rho GTPase activation : turning on the switch Small GTPases of the Rho family are key regulators of eukaryotic cellular architecture [ 7 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15694851" target="_blank">15694851</a>]<br></li>
<li>The protein encoded by WASF1 , a member of the Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome protein family , plays a critical role downstream of Rac , which is a Rho family of small GTPases , in regulating the actin cytoskeleton required for membrane rufflffling .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28529955" target="_blank">28529955</a>]<br></li>
<li>Ruffling is caused by an extensive rearrangement of the actin cytoskeleton , which is mediated by the activation of small GTPases of the Rho family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12360287" target="_blank">12360287</a>]<br></li>
<li>After bacterial internalization , the activation of Rho family GTPases and the actin cytoskeleton rearrangements are reversed by the TTSS bacterial effector SptP , a GTPase-activating protein for several Rho family members ( Fu and Galán , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>After bacterial internalization , the activation of Cdc42 and Rac is terminated by another bacterial protein , SptP , which promotes GTP hydrolysis by Rho family members7 ,8 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12360287" target="_blank">12360287</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several guanine nucleotide exchange factors ( GEFs ) of the small Rho GTP-binding protein family possess PH ( pleckstrin homology ) domains , enabling interaction with PI ( 3,4,5 ) P3 and favoring the Rho GTPases translocation to the plasma membrane .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29276700" target="_blank">29276700</a>]<br></li>
<li>Through its TTSS , Salmonella delivers SopE , SopE2 , and SopB , which differentially activate different Rho family GTPase members either directly ( SopE and SopE2 ) or indirectly via the stimulation of the endogenous exchange factor SGEF ( SopB ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE and SopE2 are 70 % identical at the level of amino acid sequence ( 27 ) and apparently bind to the same regions of Rho GTPases as the eukaryotic GEFs despite lacking the typical eukaryotic GTPase-binding motif ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both directly through action of the bacterially encoded exchange factors SopE and SopE2 and indirectly through activation of the endogenous RhoG exchange factor SGEF by SopB , this bacterial pathogen orchestrates the coordinated activation of specific Rho family GTPase members to stimulate specific cellular responses .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>These cellular responses are the direct consequence of the stimulation of the Rho family GTPases Cdc42 and Rac1 by the bacterially encoded exchange factors SopE and SopE2 , which cat ¬ * To whom correspondence should be addressed ( e-mail : jorge .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11163217" target="_blank">11163217</a>]<br></li>
<li>Salmonella entry is the consequence of the activation of the Rho family GTPases Cdc42 and Rac1 by the bacterial-encoded exchange factors SopE and SopE2 ( GalaÂn and Zhou , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11736992" target="_blank">11736992</a>]<br></li>
<li>Membrane rufﬂing occurs subsequent to the activation of the Rho family GTPases Cdc42 and Rac1 by bacterial effector proteins that mimic eukaryotic guanine nucleotide exchange factors ( GEFs ) , such as SopE and SopE2 ( 36 , 74 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20368348" target="_blank">20368348</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE , SopE2 and SopB target the RhoGTPase switch and promote activation of the Rho family members Cdc42 and Rac , leading to actin remodeling .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16182381" target="_blank">16182381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Bacterial internalization is mediated by the SPI-1 T3SS effectors SopE , SopE2 , and SopB , which activate the Rho family of GTPases Rac1 , Cdc42 and RhoG [ 9,10 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24098123" target="_blank">24098123</a>]<br></li>
<li>The cocktail of bacterial effectors established to effect actin cytoskeleton rearrangements includes three Sops ( Salmonella outer proteins ) that directly ( SopE and E2 ) or indirectly ( SopB ) target small GTPases of the Rho family , key upstream regulators of host cell actin rearrangements , as well as SipA and SipC ( Patel and Galan , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19732055" target="_blank">19732055</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , SopE is able to activate several different members of the Rho family in vitro , including Rac1 , Cdc42 , RhoA , and RhoG ( 10 , 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26443572" target="_blank">26443572</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regulation of cortical actin dynamics in response to extracellular stimuli has been ascribed to members of the Rho family of small GTPases , which includes RhoA , Rac1 , and Cdc42 ( Hall , 1998 ; Van Aelst and D'Souza-Schorey , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11256999" target="_blank">11256999</a>]<br></li>
<li>SopE can efficiently and directly activate members of the Rho GTPase family of small G-proteins , including Rac-1 , Rac-2 , Cdc42 , RhoG , and , to a lesser extent , RhoA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11036630" target="_blank">11036630</a>]<br></li>
<li>Discussion Many bacterial pathogens target Rho family GTPases with a variety of toxins ( Aktories , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>[ 28 ] Patel J.C. , Galan J.E. , Investigating the function of Rho family GTPases during Salmonella/host cell interactions , Methods Enzymol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19775595" target="_blank">19775595</a>]<br></li>
<li>Role of Rho family GTPases in S. Typhimurium entry into ﬁbroblasts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20368348" target="_blank">20368348</a>]<br></li>
<li>Requirement of Rho family GTPases for entry of S. Typhimurium SL1344 ( wild type ) and MD706 ( SPI-1 ) strains into NRK-49F ﬁbroblasts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20368348" target="_blank">20368348</a>]<br></li>
<li>Bokoch , G. M. ( 2000 ) Regulation of cell function by Rho family GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12960245" target="_blank">12960245</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cooperative activation of PI3K by Ras and Rho family small GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29276700" target="_blank">29276700</a>]<br></li>
<li>bacterial internalization through signaling to Rho family GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21501827" target="_blank">21501827</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model for Salmonella signaling to Rho family GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17074883" target="_blank">17074883</a>]<br></li>
<li>T3SS-1 effectors target Rho family guanosine triphosphatases ( GTPases ) and actin-binding proteins to induce membrane ruffling , macropinocytosis , and nuclear responses leading to inflammation ( 5 -- 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21934108" target="_blank">21934108</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also SopB was shown to indirectly stimulate Rho family GTPases and nuclear responses [ 56 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29522566" target="_blank">29522566</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Rho family GTPases lead to activation of pro-inﬂammatory signaling pathways involving MAP kinases and NF-κB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21716657" target="_blank">21716657</a>]<br></li>
<li>Vega , F.M. , and Ridley , A.J. ( 2007 ) SnapShot : Rho family GTPases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23869992" target="_blank">23869992</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because GFP-SifA still localizes to peroxisomes in pex25 mutants , it is plausible that a common protein exists on both yeast peroxisomes and mamma-lian endosomes that recruits SifA to the relevant membrane systems and link it to the local conserved Rho family members .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20739463" target="_blank">20739463</a>]<br></li>
<li>Small GTPases belonging to the Rho family are involved in multiple regulatory aspects related to cyto-skeleton function in mammalian cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21435037" target="_blank">21435037</a>]<br></li>
